{
  "doc_id": "58233",
  "text": "In obese children, as in adults, evidence exists on an association between insulin resistance and hepatic accumulation of fat [CITATION_1] . This has been related to a reduced effect of insulin action on adipose tissue, with a consequent lack of suppression of lipolysis and thus an increased flux of free fatty acids to the liver (55). This effect, together with an increased hepatic lipogenesis related to hyperinsulinemia, is responsible for the accumulation of triglycerides in the hepatocytes and the development of steatosis [CITATION_2] . Increased levels of liver enzymes, particularly alanine aminotransferase (ALT), increase with worsening insulin sensitivity [CITATION_3] . Based on the association of steatosis and increased ALT with insulin resistance and IGT in obese adults and children, steatosis has been suggested as the hepatic manifestation of the metabolic syndrome [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
